  <body>
    <segment id="1" parent="19" relname="span">There is a gardening revolution going on.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="14" relname="span">
People are planting flower baskets with living plants, </segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="3" relname="elaboration">
mixing many types in one container for a full summer of floral beauty.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="16" relname="purpose">
To create your own &quot;Victorian&quot; bouquet of flowers, </segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="16" relname="span">
choose varying shapes, sizes and forms, besides a variety of complementary colors.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="6" relname="elaboration">
Plants that grow tall should be surrounded by smaller ones and filled with others that tumble over the side of a hanging basket.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="11" relname="span">
Leaf textures and colors will also be important.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="8" relname="elaboration">
There is the silver-white foliage of dusty miller, the feathery threads of lotus vine floating down from above, the deep greens, or chartreuse, even the widely varied foliage colors of the coleus.</segment>
    <segment id="10">


Christian Science Monitor, April, 1983</segment>
